£2-a-day drug could reduce heart attack threat
Thousands of heart patients could benefit from a £2-a-day drug after officials suggest it be given to more patients and taken for a longer period of time.
The anticoagulant drug ticagrelor may reduce the risk of another heart attack in people with heart disease.
This drug, when taken for 12 months after a heart attack, reduces the risk of stroke or another heart attack.
The National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence (NICE), the regulator for the NHS, recommends that patients continue taking the drug for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease.
But now NHS regulator NICE is recommending that patients continue taking the drug for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease.
Around 140,000 people in England suffer from a heart attack each year, and a quarter of these will go on to suffer another heart attack or stroke.
Heart attacks and strokes are caused by plaque deposits of fatty material in the walls of arteries.
If the plaque breaks off, it can cause blood clots, which can block blood flow to the heart and lead to a heart attack.
If the clot moves, it can enter the bloodstream and block blood flow to the brain, causing a stroke.
People who have already experienced a heart attack are at higher risk of having another heart attack.
Ticagrelor, made by British company AstraZeneca and marketed as Brilique, reduces the risk by reducing the formation of blood clots.
NICE draft guidance published today recommends that patients take 90 mg of ticagrelor for 12 months, followed by 60 mg of ticagrelor and aspirin twice a day for three years.
Professor Carole Longson, director of NICE&#39;s Center for Health Technology Assessment, said: &quot;Despite effective secondary prevention treatments, up to a quarter of people who have had a heart attack will have another heart attack or stroke, often with serious consequences.&quot;
The fear of relapse can have a significant negative impact on a person&#39;s quality of life.
Evidence shows that ticagrelor, taken together with aspirin, is effective in reducing the risk of another heart attack and stroke in people who have had a heart attack.
We are pleased that the interim recommendation for ticagrelor will provide more treatment options for thousands of people who could benefit.
Because there is limited information on the efficacy and safety of ticagrelor beyond three years, particularly the risk of bleeding, the draft guidance does not recommend continuation of treatment with ticagrelor beyond this period.
