China’s Mars plan is coming
Our country&#39;s Mars exploration mission will orbit, land, and patrol at one time, which has never been done before abroad.
Our country&#39;s Mars exploration and launch goal is to orbit, land, and patrol in one step. This task is quite difficult.
Because it takes 26 months for Mars exploration to reach a time window, experts are rigorously formulating engineering plans and striving to launch my country&#39;s first Mars probe within this window of 2020.
According to Xu Dazhe, although my country&#39;s aircraft have entered deep space, it is still indispensable to complete the Mars exploration mission. Exploring Mars means that China has truly entered the era of deep space exploration.
&quot;Only once every two or three years does Mars have the opportunity to be closest to the Earth. Launching a Mars probe at this point in time is the most energy-saving for the launch vehicle.&quot;
&quot;Considering the quality of the Mars probe, my country&#39;s Long March 5 carrier rocket will complete the launch mission.&quot;
Our country&#39;s Mars exploration mission will orbit, land, and patrol at once. This form has never been seen abroad. Foreign countries once planned to orbit and land at once, but the landing failed.
Mars exploration involves many technical fields. What is special is that although the Mars rover is a space probe, it has distinctive characteristics compared with ordinary space probes.
In other words, the Mars rover must have the ability to determine the driving route and detect obstacles and dangers.
Pang Zhihao, a researcher at the Fifth Academy of the China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation, said that the reason why humans are so interested in Mars exploration is because Mars exploration has important scientific and technological significance, and is even related to the future of mankind.
At present, Mars has become the most studied planet by humans besides the earth. The history of humans using space probes to explore Mars almost runs through the entire history of human spaceflight.
Therefore, humans hope to one day establish a residential base on Mars, eventually immigrating to Mars and turning it into a second home for humans.
A large number of signs also indicate that Mars was likely to be the same as the current Earth. It only took billions of years of evolution to become a thin atmosphere, lower temperature, and depleted water sources.
Therefore, exploration or manned landing on Mars for research can provide plans to prevent the earth from becoming a second Mars where humans cannot survive.
As of June 2016, a total of 114 lunar explorations and 43 Mars explorations had been carried out around the world.
However, since the 1990s, humans have conducted a total of 18 Mars explorations, while only 14 lunar explorations have been conducted.
There are currently 5 Mars orbiters and 2 Mars rovers in operation, but only 1 lunar orbiter and 1 lunar lander are in operation.
The world&#39;s major space powers have formulated exploration plans targeting the Mars system. It can be seen that today&#39;s Mars exploration is hotter than lunar exploration.
On November 5, 2013, India launched its first Mars probe &quot;Mangalyan&quot; and became the first country in Asia to successfully detect Mars.
&quot;Mangalian&quot; is used to study the surface, atmosphere and mineral characteristics of Mars, and to explore whether there is methane and signs of life on Mars.
The most difficult part of this mission is that after the probe enters the Martian atmosphere, the aerodynamic shape and parachute deceleration only have one chance.
According to Sun Zezhou, chief designer of the Mars probe at the General Headquarters of the Fifth Academy of China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation, the Mars exploration mission faces many technical challenges.
The atmospheric pressure of Mars is very low, only 1% of the atmospheric pressure on the Earth&#39;s surface, and has a high degree of uncertainty.
Scientists do not yet have a thorough understanding of factors such as its changes and storm characteristics.
Mars often forms dust storms similar to those on Earth in the summer, which will cause the solar energy received by the rover to drop sharply. A &quot;sleep&quot; mode must be designed for the rover to wait patiently for the dust storm to pass.
At the same time, the Martian atmosphere also reduces solar illumination, which poses problems in the energy supply for Mars exploration.
This requires the detector&#39;s solar wing area to be larger, and it needs to be constantly adjusted to strive to align with the direction of the sun.
Also, the gravity on the surface of Mars is only 38% of that of the Earth, but it is much greater than the gravity on the surface of the moon, so the detector needs more power.
&quot;The core and most difficult part of this Mars exploration mission is the aerodynamic shape and parachute deceleration process after the probe enters the Martian atmosphere. There is only one chance, and success must be ensured.&quot;
Sun Zezhou said that due to the long distance between the Earth and Mars, the entire process cannot be controlled in real time by the ground, so it must be completed independently by the detector.
Since there is not that much propellant to offset such a high speed, when landing on Mars, deceleration depends on the Martian atmosphere. However, the Martian atmosphere is difficult to simulate on the ground.
Pang Zhihao said that generally speaking, the method of detecting Mars is similar to the method of detecting the moon, which is also &quot;circling, landing, patrolling, and returning&quot; to ultimately achieve the goal of manned landing on Mars.
Since Mars is much farther from the earth than the moon is, detecting Mars requires overcoming a series of more complex technical difficulties.
