During the match between Australia and Japan, the environmental conditions in the water polo pools gradually deteriorated, but officials emphasized that they would restore the water quality of the two pools to their original colors on the 11th.
Rio Olympics spokesman Mario Andrada said: &quot;Yesterday afternoon, the alkalinity of the water in the diving pool first became weaker.&quot;
&quot;We learned about a range of possible causes of discoloration in pool water and the alkalinity of the water.&quot;
The Aquatics Center conducted a series of water quality tests and hundreds of divers and swimmers used the pool to ensure that water quality standards were met. &quot;
&quot;We have been following normal procedures these days, but we may have overlooked the impact that more athletes may have on water quality.&quot;
&quot;But the change in water color definitely has no impact on human health, especially on athletes.&quot;
&quot;This independent team confirmed our assessment and the steps we took to restore the pool to its normal color and chemical state.&quot;
&quot;We had hoped that the pool would be back to normal color in the morning, but the rain has affected the speed of recovery.&quot;
