Gracia is a cute female toucan, exuding the atmosphere of a tropical rainforest.
In the Central American country of Costa Rica, Toucan Gracia and her story have long been a household name.
At a press conference on August 10, Gracia finally appeared after recovering from the operation, showing off her brand new 3D printed plastic beak.
This toucan, whose beak was broken off a year and a half ago and was dying, has finally been given a new lease of life.
This day not only announces that it has recovered 100% to health, it is also the day that it moves into a luxurious aviary and meets its human friends who care about it.
Gracia was a little shy when she first entered her new home, but soon she became lively, rolling and playing in the water basin and eating grapes with her new beak.
To remind people of the damage it had suffered, technicians did not color its new beak, but retained the original white color of the 3D printing material.
The outside of the beak is a thin sheath of horn, and the inside is hollow, with only some thin bony support rods arranged staggered.
Despite this internal reinforcement, the toucan&#39;s beak is fragile and can shatter when injured.
The animal rescue center, ornithologists and an American 3D printing company worked together to make several &quot;test beaks&quot; for Gracia, and finally created the &quot;perfect beak&quot; that best suited her.
Gracia is now able to use her new beak proficiently to drink water, eat, and even pick up small grains.
&quot;The design of the final product took about 2 months, and it only took 4 or 5 hours to print it.&quot;
&quot;3D printing is not a future technology. It has actually entered our lives.&quot; Thomas Lange, chairman of the American SG3D Printing Company, said in an interview with Xinhua International reporters.
In January 2015, a toucan named Gracia was found covered in blood on a farm in Gracia, Alajuela Province, central Costa Rica.
At that time, its upper beak was brutally broken by a group of young people. It was completely unable to eat and was in critical condition.
After Gracia&#39;s tragic story was reported by the media, it aroused a wave of calls against animal cruelty in Costa Rica and abroad.
People are calling for stricter animal protection laws and greater punishment for abusers.
People came spontaneously and tried their best to help Gracia return to her pre-injury life as much as possible.
Even Chuck Hull, the inventor of 3D printing technology, participated in the design of Gracia’s upper beak.
&quot;Gracia&#39;s situation is very special. The remaining part of its upper beak is less than 1 centimeter, so it brings many difficulties to install a new beak.&quot;
&quot;We first scanned Gracia, then designed and made an extended prosthesis that was slightly longer than the remaining part of its upper beak, and fixed it to its upper beak with glue.&quot;
&quot;This can reduce further invasive damage to Gracia.&quot; Lange told Xinhua International reporters.
Before installing the prosthesis, staff had to clean Gracia&#39;s beak every day to prevent infection.
Thousands of miles away, the story of Toucan Gracia moved the famous documentary director Paula Heredia and Discovery News Channel producer John Hoffman.
They recorded every detail of Gracia&#39;s process of installing her new beak and recorded a documentary &quot;Toucan Country,&quot; which was broadcast on the Animal Planet channel this month.
The documentary &quot;Toucan Country&quot; shows people how a little toucan can change a country and how it can get citizens to participate in the fight against animal cruelty.
Core tip: Japanese oil companies are especially wary of the rise of China&#39;s small independent refineries known as &quot;teapots.&quot;
