Ultraviolet rays not only darken the skin of students, but also cause sunburn. How can the skin survive military training smoothly without getting sunburned?
Sunscreen packages are generally marked with SPF and PA. SPF refers to the sun protection index, which is against UVB ultraviolet rays. Our common SPF indexes are 15, 30, 50, etc.
Products marked with PA are for UVA, so that the sunscreen will play a more effective role. Usually, the intensity of PA is represented by +, and one more + indicates that the effective protection time is extended.
Oily skin should choose water-based sunscreen products with strong penetration, and sunscreen spray is also a good choice.
Dry skin should choose cream-based sunscreen products; there are generally no strict regulations for normal skin, and it is a burden to apply any skin care products to sensitive skin. It is recommended to choose purely physical sunscreen products.
Remember to apply sunscreen half an hour in advance as it takes time for sunscreen products to fully penetrate into the skin.
Military training requires a long period of sun exposure. Sunscreen needs to be applied every two hours to have a lasting effect. Don&#39;t be lazy.
Since your skin has just been irritated by the sun, do not use whitening products immediately after returning from military training.
After exposure to the sun during military training, if possible, ice cubes wrapped in a towel can be used to cool the burned skin to slow down the local heat.
