The upgraded Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal branch channels Laowanfu River and Beidaliu Channel will collect tolls from September 1.
These two tributary waterways are being reconstructed and constructed using social financing methods, and the fees have been approved by relevant departments of the provincial government.
The Laowanfu River channel flows through Jinxiang and Yutai, and then enters the main channel of the Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal via Nanyang Lake, with a total length of 32.5 kilometers.
According to the needs of navigation, the Laowanfu River channel has been maintained and reconstructed, and local water depths have been dredged, and local sharp bends have been cut and straightened, so that navigation conditions have been improved.
The waterway flows through Jinxiang County and Rencheng District, passes through Nanyang Lake and enters the main channel of the Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal, with a total length of 19 kilometers.
The reconstruction project of the two waterways started construction in February 2011 and completed the handover and acceptance in January 2015. The main investment, construction and operation entity is the Jining Anping Canal Logistics Service Center.
In accordance with the principle of &quot;loan construction, fee repayment&quot;, Jining Anping Canal Logistics Service Center collects waterway tolls based on the charging standards approved by the Shandong Provincial Price Bureau.
Among them, the basic toll is charged at RMB 1.75/dwt, and the mileage toll is charged at RMB 0.05/km DWT.
The toll collection period is from June 15, 2016 to June 14, 2019.
The reporter learned from the Jining Port and Navigation Bureau that there are currently four toll channels in Jining, namely the Zhushui River Channel, the Baima River Channel, the Beidaliu Channel, and the Laowanfu River Channel.
The four waterways are tributary channels of the Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal, and they have all been upgraded using social financing.
The Zhushui River channel upgrading and reconstruction project is the first project to adopt the &quot;government + market&quot; model for the construction of inland river port and shipping infrastructure in Shandong Province. The government accounts for the main investment and social funds supplement the funding gap.
Branch waterways such as the Baima River, Laowanfu River, and Beidaliu River adopt a purely market-oriented operation method.
Funds allocated by the national finance cannot meet the needs of project construction, which restricts the progress of waterway upgrades.
The use of social funds for the construction of public infrastructure meets the requirements of national policies and has also become a way to break the financial bottleneck.
