The Greenland shark, also known as the small-headed sleeper shark, is widely distributed in the North Atlantic waters around Greenland and Iceland. It reaches a length of 4 to 5 meters when it reaches adulthood.
But their growth rate is extremely slow, sometimes only about 1 centimeter per year, which suggests that Greenland sharks may have an exceptionally long lifespan.
Traditional dating methods usually use the calcified tissue of animals. In some sharks, fin ridges can be used, but this kind of calcified tissue is very rare in Greenland sharks.
The new study, led by Julius Nielsen of the University of Copenhagen in Denmark, turned to the lens of the Greenland shark&#39;s eye for radiocarbon dating.
This method has been used to determine the age of whales before, but this is the first time it has been used to determine the age of fish such as sharks.
Their analysis showed that the lifespan of the largest shark was estimated to be 392 years, with a margin of error of 120 years.
This means that the shark is at least 272 years old and may be as old as 512 years old.
In addition, it is said that female Greenland sharks do not reach sexual maturity until they are about 4 meters in length, which means they do not reach adulthood until they are at least 156 years old.
The researchers therefore wrote in the paper that the Greenland shark is the longest-lived vertebrate known on earth, surpassing the previous longevity champion, the right whale (211 years old).
