So when the app this week gave some users a filter that created slanted eyes, weird teeth and a pink face, some critics called it a racial caricature of &quot;yellow&quot; Asians.
They even wonder whether these recurring issues mean the company has a larger problem with diversity.
Reports from The Verge and Motherboard sparked outrage on Wednesday after Snapchat said it was removing the feature.
The company explained that the filter was a tribute to the anime character, not a satire of Asians.
But for observers who have experienced racism, the filter reminds them of hurtful stereotypes in reality.
Others are also staunchly opposed to the cartoon characters.
A Korean-American art student who tweeted about the photos, which were widely shared, said in an email that the filters were &quot;disturbing and uncomfortable to say the least.&quot;
She added: &quot;It&#39;s hard to differentiate between the extremely disgusting caricature of Asia and the effect of the filter.&quot;
Although it’s not just yellow people in the filter, yellow people are extremely devalued.
Snapchat isn&#39;t the only company touching these cultural lines.
From corporate boardrooms to Hollywood and the devices we carry, American culture seems to be constantly promoting diversity and inclusion.
Snapchat’s large young population, which is more racially diverse than older generations, may be sensitive.
When a Snapchat filter creates an image that insults users, 25-year-old Katie Zhu said in an interview on Thursday: &quot;It&#39;s harder for things like this to escape people&#39;s attention than it used to be.&quot;
On Thursday, Zhu, a product manager and engineer at Medium, decided to delete her Snapchat account and encouraged others to do the same.
In an article for Medium and in a phone interview, she said she believed the racial controversy reflected a lack of racial diversity in Snapchat&#39;s hiring process.
Ms. Zhu criticized the company for having a majority white workforce and an all-male leadership and ended her post with a hashtag: #DeleteSnapchat.
Ms. Zhu, who is Chinese American, said: “Either they don’t have people of color on their staff to make decisions like this, or they have some people of color on their staff but they’re not in a position where they can speak out.”
Other observers shared her complaints about not being responded to by Snapchat.
The company does not release data on employee diversity and says it is a private company.
On Thursday, Snapchat declined to discuss the racial backgrounds of its employees, but a spokesperson said the company recently hired a recruiter to focus on underrepresented groups and drive internal inclusion efforts.
Ms. Zhu said she would close her Snapchat account: &quot;I wonder if they need more users like us who are against this behavior.&quot;
Congressional panel says military officials distorted ISIS intelligence
Officials at U.S. Central Command changed intelligence reports to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than what actually happened, a congressional panel said in a report released Thursday.
The interim report comes from a task force formed by the Republican chairs of the House Armed Services Committee, the Intelligence Committee and the House Appropriations Committee’s defense subcommittee. The report said there was &quot;widespread dissatisfaction&quot; among Central Command intelligence analysts who said superiors were tampering with their assessments of the U.S. war against the Islamic State.
Central Command (Centcom), located in Tampa, Florida, is the military headquarters responsible for overseeing U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
According to a news release about the report, &quot;Intelligence reviewed by Central Command&#39;s senior leaders paints a more optimistic picture of U.S. counterterrorism operations than is actually the case and is consistently more optimistic than analyzes by other intelligence agencies.&quot;
&quot;CENTCOM&#39;s actions are unacceptable. Our warfighters are suffering the consequences of war while high-level policymakers receive faulty analysis,&quot; said a Republican representative from California.
Central Command&#39;s leadership problems extend to the highest levels of the agency.
The report details longstanding problems in Central Command&#39;s description and analysis of U.S. training of Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
While there is no conclusive evidence that senior Obama administration officials ordered changes to the reports, the reports describe analysts who felt they were under pressure from Central Command leaders to target the Islamic State (ISIS or ISIL). threat to express a more optimistic view.
&quot;During the first half of 2015, many Central Command press releases, statements, and congressional testimony were much more optimistic than the actual situation,&quot; the report said.
For example, a Central Command official publicly stated that a major military operation to retake Mosul may be launched as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq&#39;s second largest city, remains under the control of the Islamic State.
&quot;After months of investigation, this outcome is clear,&quot; Rep. Mike Pompeo, R-Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, most senior intelligence officials at U.S. Central Command manipulated the command’s intelligence products to conceal the threat from the Islamic State in Iraq.
Republicans established a task force after learning from analysts that intelligence on the Islamic State had been manipulated.
Following this report released Thursday, more discoveries will be made as the investigation continues.
The Defense Department&#39;s inspector general also has a long-running investigation into Central Command.
Democratic members of the House Intelligence Committee released its findings on Thursday, echoing some of the conclusions of the Republican task force.
&quot;Between 2014 and 2015, Central Command developed an overly narrow process for intelligence assessments of the Islamic State and Iraqi peacekeepers,&quot; Representative Schiff, the committee&#39;s top Democrat, said in a statement. &quot;
Mr. Schiff said the process &quot;impeded the release of intelligence,&quot; lowered analyst morale and &quot;failed to accept dissent.&quot;
But Mr. Schiff and Democrats also said they found no evidence that the White House sought to pressure Central Command analysts to make their conclusions fit &quot;presets or political narratives.&quot;
The Daily Beast reported the preliminary results of the congressional investigation on Tuesday.
Last August, The New York Times reported that the Pentagon inspector general began an investigation after receiving complaints from Central Command analysts.
Pentagon spokesman Navy Maj. Patrick Evans said in a statement that the Department of Defense would not comment on the congressional report until the inspector general&#39;s investigation is concluded.
But he said: &quot;Experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and the intelligence community and the Department of Defense encourage healthy dialogue on these important national security topics.&quot;
The investigation has implications beyond the question of whether the U.S.-led bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria has been successful, as a growing number of Defense Department officials claim.
But last year, the claims raised public questions about the extent to which President Obama could trust Central Command&#39;s assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis zones.
Criticisms about ISIS intelligence are reminiscent of a controversy more than a decade ago, when Central Command intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker wrote a research article arguing that George W. Bush&#39;s administration ignored the objections of numerous analysts , insisted on sending small forces to Iraq and paid little regard to the aftermath of the 2003 invasion.
Mr Hook played a key role in the intelligence push against the Islamic State.
Last year, officials said Mr. Hook&#39;s team concluded that airstrikes targeting Islamic State refineries did not significantly cut into the terror group&#39;s financial revenue because the group built makeshift refineries and continued to sell oil on the black market. This is contrary to the published statement.
According to a report in Time in September, Central Command did not announce the discovery to the public.
Central Command Commander Lloyd Austin III came under fire last year after lawyers reviewed Senate testimony that offered an overly optimistic assessment of the war.
General Austin retired in April and is currently being replaced at Central Command by Joseph Votel.
