Shabby Depression-era Food in &quot;A Big Feast&quot;
In March 1933, newly elected President Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat in the Oval Office enjoying lunch.
A gourmet, President Roosevelt favored Fifth Avenue delicacies such as foie gras and Maryland waterfish stew.
His menu that day was simple: deviled eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes, and fruit pudding for dessert.
&quot;It&#39;s about sharing food through thick and thin with people who are suffering,&quot; said Jean Ziegelman.
Her husband, Andrew Coe, added: &quot;It also speaks to the way Americans eat.&quot;
The couple, who live in Brooklyn Heights, are both food historians.
Mr. Coe&#39;s last book, &quot;Chowder,&quot; was about Chinese food in America, and Ms. Ziegelman&#39;s &quot;97 Orchards&quot; tells the story of the lives of ghetto tenants through food.
Their new book, &quot;A Big Feast,&quot; to be published by Harper on Tuesday, is a history of food in America during the Great Depression.
After sharing some food insights, they met a reporter at Eisenberg&#39;s sandwich shop. This simple lunch counter in the Flatiron District has been open since the crash of 1929.
Ms. Ziegelman, 54, ordered a cream cheese and chopped olive sandwich, while Mr. Coe, 57, ordered the turkey, mashed potatoes and vegetable platter.
The reporter ordered a meatloaf, which the couple thought would be appropriate for a discussion of Depression-era eating.
“Bread was very popular at the time,” Ms. Ziegelman said.
There were peanut bread, liver bread, and soybean bread.
They&#39;re all made with one ingredient and an inexpensive topping that can be poured over the ingredient.
Imagine your dinner is filled with peanuts.
Mr. Coe grimaced.
&quot;They must be like lead in your stomach,&quot; he said.
In the years before the Great Depression, every meal in America was a buffet, especially in the suburbs.
A group of women cooked for the male farm workers, and there were freshly made pies for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
During World War I, it was Americans who brought food to hungry Europeans. &quot;A Big Feast&quot; chronicles how the country suddenly ceased to be a place of plenty.
Mr. Coe explained why he and his wife wrote the book: &quot;At a time when food had become a major source of discomfort for Americans.&quot;
Another unpleasant topic is shabby new foods: &quot;mystery foods&quot; such as breads and stews have become main courses, and stews are &quot;the best way to cook leftovers,&quot; Ms. Ziegelman said, because chefs You can use the cream in the sauce to mask unpalatable ingredients.
Fresh fruit was replaced by cheaper dried fruit.
Meat, which has starred on American dinner tables for years, has become a rare luxury.
A strange smorgasbord that only considers calories and puts nutrition first before taste or even basic cooking common sense.
While researching the book, which includes various recipes, Ms. Ziegelman created a grilled onion stuffed with peanut oil.
&quot;It&#39;s not something you see often at the dinner table,&quot; Mr. Coe said.
&quot;It&#39;s so weird,&quot; Ms. Ziegelman said.
Peanut oil doesn&#39;t mix well with grilled onions at all.
This is a feature of many family budget meals.
Uniquely in history, home economists such as Louis Stanley, head chef of the Federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943, influenced the country&#39;s eating habits.
They published recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, encouraging women to be &quot;budget-savvy&quot; and brave enough to turn terrible meals like creamy pasta with carrots into gourmet meals.
&quot;A Hearty Feast&quot; is a sumptuous &quot;historic treasure&quot;.
Particularly interesting are the government&#39;s responses to hungry people, such as President Herbert Hoover&#39;s &quot;I can&#39;t do other people&#39;s business&quot; attitude.
While he openly extols the simple Iowa farmhouse of his childhood, he eats like a millionaire.
Mr. Coe said: &quot;He likes to eat European-style Western food, such as fish with cucumber sauce.&quot;
He wore an evening gown and dined in a gilded dining room.
He is clearly out of touch with the people.
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake if his wife, Eleanor, hadn&#39;t encouraged him to set an example with his diet.
As the book notes, Ms. Roosevelt hired a housekeeper who had no interest in taste, so the food in the White House was “not only the nastiest food in Washington, but also the worst-cooked.”
Once America got back on track, many of the Depression-era cooking styles were abandoned.
What remains, Ms. Ziegelman said, is our focus on calories and nutrition and applying science to cooking.
The couple said that while writing the book, they learned more about Ms. Ziegelman&#39;s mother&#39;s eating habits, such as how she didn&#39;t throw food away.
&quot;She was very afraid of wasting food,&quot; Mr Coe said.
“She actually made a lot of people sick,” Ms. Ziegelman recalled.
For example, there was a &quot;cream puff&quot; incident.
After removing the plates, she and Mr. Coe brought out a dessert they had prepared at home: the preserves pudding that President Roosevelt had eaten for lunch.
&quot;It&#39;s called candied fruit,&quot; Ms. Ziegelman said, adding that giving a trendy name to a common dish was &quot;a common trick.&quot;
There is no whipped cream in this dessert, just preserved fruit, a little flour, sugar, water and cinnamon.
Everyone reluctantly dipped their spoons into the thick brown paste.
Surprisingly, this dessert tastes pretty good.
Mr. Coe took a second and third spoonful.
He thought it was an acceptable and affordable dessert, so he told his wife: &quot;It would taste better with some chopped walnuts.&quot;
