Staying up late to watch Olympic games can easily damage your heart
The Brazilian Olympic Games are in full swing, and even though it is midnight in China when the games are broadcast, many citizens will stay up late to watch.
In this regard, doctors specifically remind you that staying up late to watch games has health risks and may cause cardiovascular disease.
If you stay up late for a long time, this hormone will still be secreted in large amounts, and the human body will continue to be in a state of tension and excitement, unable to recover normally, which can easily cause vasoconstriction, increase blood pressure, and thus cause cardiovascular disease.
Han Zhiyuan specifically reminded that people with cardiovascular risk factors such as high blood pressure, high blood sugar, high blood lipids, smoking habits, family history, etc., will be more likely to develop cardiovascular disease if they stay up late.
If you stay up late for a long time, not only your cardiovascular function will be affected, but your gastrointestinal function, immune system, and neuroendocrine system will also be affected, and your risk of cancer will even increase.
For elderly friends, Han Zhiyuan suggested that they try not to stay up late to watch Olympic games, especially those with a history of cardiovascular disease.
During the last &quot;World Cup&quot; football match, Han Zhiyuan received a patient in his 60s. The cause of his myocardial infarction may be related to staying up late to watch the game.
Han Zhiyuan said that since this year, his department has treated some patients with myocardial infarction or stroke around the age of 25. This is largely caused by the patient&#39;s long-term lifestyle of staying up late.
1. Don’t stay up late every day. Occasionally stay up late to watch your favorite sports. For other sports, you might as well wait until the next day to watch the replay of the event.
2. When staying up late, replenish water in a timely manner and eat more fruits to prevent blood vessel blockage and enhance the body&#39;s immunity.
