During the Cold War, the Soviet Union transported missiles into Cuba, which almost led to a nuclear war between the United States and the Soviet Union.
This incident is regarded as the peak of the Cold War and is known as the &quot;Cuban Missile Crisis&quot; in history.
But what is less known is that also during the Cold War, a strong solar storm almost caused the United States to launch a nuclear war against the Soviet Union. This event was not announced to the public for the first time until August 9 by researchers.
On May 23, 1967, a severe solar storm caused severe interference to the U.S. military&#39;s radar and radio communications in the Arctic.
These radars were part of the U.S. ballistic missile warning system and were used to monitor Soviet missiles.
This paper, written by researchers at the University of Colorado, interviewed U.S. military personnel who were involved in forecasting and analyzing solar activity at the time, and reviewed unclassified literature.
The paper writes that in the 1960s, in order to prevent the Soviet Union from suddenly launching a nuclear war, the U.S. Air Force always had some fighter planes carrying nuclear warheads flying in the sky.
The U.S. military commander did not know that the culprit of this interference was the solar storm and not the Soviet Union, so he ordered the fighter planes to enter combat readiness.
Fortunately, the U.S. military&#39;s research on solar activity and its electromagnetic interference with the earth, which began in the late 1950s, finally prevented this potential military conflict.
Later, he compiled a detailed report based on information provided by the U.S. Air Force Aviation Weather Service.
As a direct consequence of this solar storm, the U.S. military has since regarded space weather as an operational concern and established a more powerful space weather forecasting system.
