NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
Venus was once habitable, according to predictions from NASA&#39;s new climate model.
Scientists at NASA&#39;s Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model that explores Venus&#39; past conditions, using tools and algorithms very similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was used to determine whether Venus, which has a hot surface, no water and an atmosphere full of carbon dioxide, once had an environment similar to Earth.
Previously, scientists believed that Venus&#39; slow rotation was due to its thick atmosphere.
But new simulations suggest Venus may have once had a thinner, Earth-like atmosphere and a similarly slow rotation.
The model also shows the early terrain of Venus.
Venus may have more dry areas than Earth, but there once was enough water and geographic variation to support life and prevent rapid evaporation.
In the early days, the brightness of sunlight shining on Venus was 30% dimmer than that of Earth.
Anthony Del Genio, a scientist at the Goddard Institute for Space Studies, explained in a press release: &quot;In the Goddard Institute for Space Studies&#39; model simulations, Venus&#39;s slow rotation causes daylight hours to last nearly two days on one side. months.&quot;
This warms the surface and creates rain that creates thick clouds that act like an umbrella and block much of the sun&#39;s heat from the ground.
The result of the simulation is that the average climate temperature of Venus is actually several degrees cooler than that of Earth today.
The model simulates the evolution of Venus that is similar to what planetary scientists previously speculated.
Although life may have once existed on Venus, over the course of billions of years, Venus was exposed to excessive temperatures and ultraviolet light.
The planet&#39;s oceans evaporate, and the water vapor is burned away by ultraviolet light.
As the hydrogen escaped, all that was left was a thick carbon dioxide atmosphere and its deadly greenhouse gas effect, creating the planet we know today.
The researchers published simulations from a new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
