Kepler measures the rotation speed of the Pleiades cluster stars
This latest mission of the Kepler Space Telescope has helped astronomers collect the most complete picture of the rotation rates of the stars in the Pleiades cluster.
New data are helping astronomers understand why the cluster&#39;s stars spin at different rates and how the rotation period correlates with the planet&#39;s composition.
&quot;We hope to learn more about the relationships between stars&#39; masses, ages, and even their solar system histories by comparing our results to other star clusters,&quot; Lusa Reible, a research scientist at Caltech&#39;s Center for Infrared Processing Analysis in Pasadena, said in a news release. relation.&quot;
The Pleiades star cluster is 445 light-years away from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster were born about 125 million years ago and are still just reaching adulthood.
They reach the highest spin rate in their lifetime.
At their highest spin rates, these mature stars eject massive stellar winds.
As these stellar winds pass through the star&#39;s magnetic field, they exert a braking effect on the star.
As a star ages, its rotation begins to slow down.
Kepler measured the rotation rate of each star by tracking the occurrence of identifiable star spots, like sunspots.
The latest rotation speed data set shows that more massive stars spin more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compared the stars to dancers, with larger dancers spinning more slowly than smaller ones.
&quot;In the &#39;ballet&#39; of the Pleiades, we find that stars that spin more slowly tend to be more massive, while stars that spin the fastest tend to be the lightest stars,&quot; Rebull said.
Because of its close proximity, the Pleiades star cluster serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory for comparing stellar masses and rotation rates.
&quot;The Pleiades provided the basis for theoretical models of bidirectional rotation of young and old stars,&quot; Rebull said.
We still have a lot to learn about how, when, and why stars slow down their rotations and &quot;put away their dancing shoes.&quot;
Rebull and her colleagues detail their latest analysis of the Pleiades cluster&#39;s rotation rate in three new papers. The three papers will be published soon in the Astronomical Journal.
